    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_ffc4cefa">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_sasjd71q">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_wjgisp5d">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_9u5ugagc">
                    Learners work in groups to explore the addition rule for probability, discovering how to calculate the probability of <q>either/or</q> events.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Discussion Prompts</title>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_c9mv2msp"><p xml:id="auto_rhtszcda">What method did your group use to solve this problem?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3h5r6ors"><p xml:id="auto_5uqa9tzz">Did you add the two probabilities? Why or why not?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_e2t4erln"><p xml:id="auto_mn8sjznf">What does <q>passing both</q> mean in this context?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_73dyf1cj"><p xml:id="auto_grmhd7hk">Can a student pass both subjects at the same time?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_0givffto"><p xml:id="auto_s86dhhqx">If we just add 75% + 60%, what do we get? Is that the correct answer?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5lc9ywyh"><p xml:id="auto_eos75b6a">What might we be counting twice if we just add the probabilities?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_wky6b7f0">
    <introduction xml:id="auto_z7t72nel">
        <p xml:id="auto_t7qibbdq">
            <alert>Work in groups</alert>
        </p>
    </introduction>

        <task xml:id="auto_omne1wz8">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_c0deq4x1">
                    A class has <m>40</m> students. 
                    <m>22</m> students play <alert>Football</alert>, 
                    <m>18</m> students play <alert>Volleyball</alert>, 
                    and <m>8</m> students play both <alert>Football</alert> and <alert>Volleyball</alert>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ny6brzce">
                    <ol marker="1.">
                        <li xml:id="auto_uursta4t">
                            <p xml:id="auto_1e21wr5h">
                                Find the probability that a randomly selected student plays <alert>Football</alert>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_a6ywaqis">
                            <p xml:id="auto_3kemxcgy">
                                Find the probability that a randomly selected student plays <alert>Volleyball</alert>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_scqo7pkf">
                            <p xml:id="auto_qd20mjml">
                                If you add the two probabilities from (a) and (b), what do you notice?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

            </statement>
            <hint>
                <p xml:id="auto_frwml3xf">
                    Remember that some students are counted in both groups.
                </p>
            </hint>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="auto_0clz64nm">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_awc61txr">
                    Find the probability that a randomly selected student plays 
                    Football <em>or</em> Volleyball.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_behdfjw8">
                    <ol marker="1.">
                        <li xml:id="auto_4hu526p2">
                            <p xml:id="auto_dgf9asxm">
                                Compare your answer with the sum of the probabilities in part (a)(<m>3</m>.). 
                                Why is there a difference?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_s2uurt9m">
                            <p xml:id="auto_t5e389gw">
                                Write a general formula for finding the probability of 
                                Event <m>A</m> or Event <m>B</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_em3z8cdv">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_sul956on">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_1mpwdd4a">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_8ydhxc9c">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_a1xm2525">
                    To formalize the addition rule for both mutually exclusive and non-mutually exclusive events.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_tup0iwki">
        <p xml:id="auto_k7t0e9sa">
            The addition rule of probability helps us find the probability that 
            <em>at least one</em> of two events occurs. 
            If A and B are two events, the probability that event A or event B 
            (or both) occurs is given by:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_fs41hx2c">
            <m>P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \cap B)</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8q3hp3cq">
            Here, <m>P(A \cap B)</m> represents the probability that both 
            events A and B occur at the same time.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ciljvqvx">
            We subtract <m>P(A \cap B)</m> because the outcomes that belong 
            to both events would otherwise be counted twice.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_z61b9cy8">
            This rule is used when events A and B are <term>not mutually exclusive</term>, 
            meaning they can occur together.
        </p>
    </insight>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_hlk3i3ym">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_lsc44csx">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_nnilqktw">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_qhlmf31i">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ud9ew25h">
                    To apply the addition rule to calculate probabilities for both mutually exclusive and non-mutually exclusive events.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_26jg06rz">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_u662b9zh">
                    Work through examples with learners step by step. Circulate during independent practice and provide assistance where needed.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_mbg4wl6i">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_pwgm7jyb">
                A standard deck of cards contains <m>52</m> cards. 
                There are <m>13</m> hearts and <m>13</m> clubs in the deck.
                If one card is drawn at random, find the probability that the card is 
                a <term>heart or a club</term>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_3nr8rapl">
                Since a single card cannot be both a heart and a club at the same time, 
                the two events are <term>mutually exclusive</term>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_m1sl49rh">
                First, find the probability of each event:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_57orzeq6">
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_4wbfmwj0">
                        <m>P(Heart) = \frac{13}{52}</m>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_zm7qt6wp">
                        <m>P(Club) = \frac{13}{52}</m>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_b989rglo">
                Because the events are mutually exclusive, we apply the addition rule:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_admc5qx0">
                <md number="yes">
                    <mrow> P(Heart or Club) \amp = P(Heart) + P(Club) </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{13}{52} + \frac{13}{52} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{26}{52} = \frac{1}{2}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_wy8ntcim">
                Therefore, the probability of drawing either a heart or a club is 
                <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>, which is equal to <m>0.5</m> or <m>50\%</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

   <example xml:id="auto_lxvh17ph">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_8rm3h6sk">
                You roll a fair six-sided die. What is the probability of rolling 
                a number divisible by <m>2</m> or <m>3</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_rjf2acd0">
                A fair six-sided die has <m>6</m> equally likely outcomes:
                <m>\{1,2,3,4,5,6\}</m>.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_jp38qr5i">
                List the numbers divisible by <m>2</m>:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_oer8c632">
                <m>\{2,4,6\}</m> → <m>3</m> numbers
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_90z4dpzu">
                List the numbers divisible by <m>3</m>:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_x6dh36ty">
                <m>\{3,6\}</m> → <m>2</m> numbers
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_5nqftehw">
                We want the numbers divisible by <m>2</m> <em>or</em> <m>3</m> 
                (the union of the two sets).
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_fvqzamlj">
                Notice that <m>6</m> appears in both sets, so we must avoid 
                counting it twice.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_4em0diwo">
                Using the inclusion–exclusion principle:
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_8xgtq1sl">
                <md>
                    <mrow>
                        P(A \text{ or } B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \text{ and } B)
                    </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_8usvmrkq">
                Compute each probability:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_m8h62mh6">
                
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_9s57u2vj">
                        <m>P(\text{divisible by 2}) = \frac{3}{6}</m>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_6p281aze">
                        <m>P(\text{divisible by 3}) = \frac{2}{6}</m>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_5nwtpahe">
                        <m>P(\text{divisible by both 2 and 3}) = P(\text{divisible by 6}) = \frac{1}{6}</m>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_bv6z9ezv">
                 <md>
                    <mrow>
                        P(\text{divisible by 2 or 3}) 
                        = \frac{3}{6} + \frac{2}{6} - \frac{1}{6}
                        = \frac{4}{6}
                        = \frac{2}{3}
                    </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
           
            <p xml:id="auto_yri6uk8m">
                Therefore, the probability of rolling a number divisible by 
                <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> is <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

